[2] Saudi Arabia, 2 Filipino nurses in ICU - media report
Date: Fri 21 Aug 2015
Source: MSN News, GMA News Online report [edited]
http://www.msn.com/en-ph/news/national/dfa-two-pinay-nurses-in-riyadh-hospital%E2%80%99s-icu-due-to-mers-cov/ar-BBlY2eX?li=AAb2fpp


Two Pinay nurses in Riyadh hospital's ICU due to MERS-CoV
---------------------------------------------------------
Two Filipino nurses have been confined at the Intensive Care Unit of a hospital in Saudi Arabia after contracting the Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV), the Department of Foreign Affairs [edited] confirmed on Friday [21 Aug 2015].

DFA spokesman Charles Jose told GMA News Online that the Philippine Embassy received an assurance from the hospital in Riyadh that the 2 nurses were receiving the "best medical treatment possible."

"[The] hospital is well-equipped with comprehensive treatment and facilities for MERS cases," Jose said in a text message.

Earlier in August [2015], the DFA confirmed that 5 Filipino paramedics who were reported to have contracted MERS-CoV were "doing well and recovering" while in isolation.

A study published on Wednesday [19 Aug 2015] claimed that a DNA vaccine for MERS-CoV is in the works and may be ready for human trials by the end of 2015. [See section [4] below for details. - Mod.MPP]

[Byline: Norman Bordadora]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[Since June 2015, when this outbreak began according to the MOH press release of several days ago, there have been a total of 8 laboratory confirmed cases in healthcare workers in Riyadh. Of these 8 cases reported to date (all reported since 21 Jul 2015, the starting date I've been using for the marked increase in cases reported from Riyadh), 6 were reported to have been expat healthcare workers. During this same period there was an additional healthcare worker confirmed as having a MERS-CoV infection in Najran. These may be the 7 healthcare workers referred to in the above media reports. - Mod.MPP]

