[4] Saudi Arabia, increasing cases and the Hajj - media report
Date: Sat 22 Aug 2015
Source: National Geographic [edited]
http://phenomena.nationalgeographic.com/2015/08/22/mers-saudi-1/


MERS Cases Increasing in Saudi Arabia, And The Hajj Is Coming
-------------------------------------------------------------
When last we checked in on the elusive disease MERS -- Middle East respiratory syndrome, caused by a virus related to the cause of the worldwide SARS epidemic in 2003 -- it had been brewing in the Gulf states for 3 years, but was triggering international alarm because of an outbreak in Korea.

That was in June [2015]. There has not been a case of MERS in Korea since July [2015]. But rather suddenly, the virus has picked up activity in the country where it got started, the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia. And that's a concern, because in a month, Saudi Arabia will host millions of temporary visitors from all over the world, making the obligatory pilgrimage known as the hajj. [The Hajj is estimated to be during the period 21-26 Sep 2015.]

Earlier in the MERS outbreak, there was international criticism (some of it written by me [Maryn McKenna]) that the Kingdom's government was being parsimonious with information about where the infection was going. As a result, the Saudi Ministry of Health now makes near-daily online reports of any MERS cases. Beginning in June [2015], things had been quiet, with no new cases reported, or at most, one per week. And then, in mid-July [2015], the numbers began to tick up again: 2 cases on [13 Jul 2015], 1 on [16 Jul 2015], 1 on [21 Jul 2015], 2 on [22 Jul 2015], 2 on [23 Jul 2015], and so on. There has been at least one case every day since [3 Aug 2015], usually more -- altogether, 76 new confirmed cases this month [August 2015].

[There were screenshots from http://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/default.aspx?PageIndex=1 inserted in the text to show the daily numbers of newly confirmed cases. - Mod.MPP]

The new run of cases is centered in one city and one hospital: King Abdulaziz Medical City, in Riyadh, the capital. This is important because, in the original MERS cases, and also in the recent Korean outbreak, hospitals were the nexus of infection, the place where the virus was exchanged between sick people, healthy companions and family members, and healthcare workers. Dr. Keiji Fukuda, an assistant director general of the WHO, said of the Korean outbreak in June [2015]: "In some instances there was close and prolonged contact between people who had infection and people who did not have infection, so for example other patients, visitors, healthcare workers in emergency rooms, so under crowded conditions and for prolonged periods of time."

According to Agence France Presse earlier this week [link to article provided: http://news.yahoo.com/saudi-mers-infections-soar-ahead-hajj-pilgrimage-100219590.html], the hospital has closed its emergency department, hoping to prevent cycling of the illness from infected to uninfected people. But, according to the daily records on the Ministry site, most of the people becoming infected are not hospital personnel. The Ministry doesn't specify where it thinks people got infected, other that to indicate Yes or No in a category headed "Contact with suspected or confirmed cases in the community or hospitals," as in this tally from Monday [17 Aug 2015]:

[A screenshot of the 17 Aug 2015 MOH update available at http://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/Statistics-2015-08-17-001.aspx - Mod.MPP]

Whether the source of the infection is the community or the hospital, neither is good news. If the hospital: Saudi Arabia has been experiencing MERS cases since mid-2012; by now, it ought to understand how healthcare transmission can be prevented. (For history, here's my original post, with an explanation of the troubling echoes of the SARS epidemic -- available at: http://www.wired.com/2012/09/coronavirus-memory-sars/.) If the community: The hajj brings an estimated 2 million people to the Kingdom, mixing in very close quarters. The government pours enormous resources into maintaining pilgrims' health, screening travelers and setting up temporary hospitals near the holy sites, but the hajj nevertheless represents prime conditions for the spread of a respiratory disease.

The fretting about possible MERS transmission during the hajj is not new: It has been a concern every year since the disease was 1st identified. For the 1st 3 of those years, the world has been fortunate, and we can hope that will be true this year as well. But there is still no specific treatment for MERS and no rapid test, and a potential vaccine is in the earliest stages of research. For those of us outside Saudi Arabia, there isn't much to do except keep watching the numbers, and hope.

[Byline: Maryn McKenna]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[An excellent assessment and overview of the current situation, and raises valid points and concerns moving forward. Prior to the outbreak in South Korea, importations of active MERS-CoV infected individuals into countries resulted in a few close contact cases, but did not result in ongoing transmission in the countries where the cases were imported. But the South Korea experience, with 186 total confirmed cases including 36 deaths, was a reminder of the SARS-CoV importations and resultant outbreaks in areas where the importations occurred during 2003.

Of note is a media report in which there is mention that Saudi Arabia is going to ban the slaughter of camels as part of the Hajj rituals this year as part of MERS-CoV prevention activities (see http://www.albawaba.com/editorchoice/keep-camel-alive-if-you-want-survive-saudi-ban-sacrificing-camels-during-hajj-prevent-s). - Mod.MPP]

